<article>

  <p>
    Naming what blocks the mind is only half a map. Desire, ill-will, dullness,
    restlessness, and doubt can be known — and still leave the question of what to
    strengthen when the weather clears. The early discourses answer with another
    list: the seven
    <span class="pali" data-pali="bojjhaṅgā" data-en="factors of awakening">bojjhaṅgā</span>
    — factors of awakening. They are not a second technique stack to install after the
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span></a>.
    They are qualities that already flicker in ordinary attention, and that deepen when
    conditions allow.
  </p>

  <p>
    Awakening here is not a brand promise. It names a direction of training — a mind
    less owned by the hindrances, more able to see clearly. The factors are trainable
    without being trophies. Miss that, and practice turns into collecting peak states.
    Catch it, and the positive map starts to make sense beside the negative one.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Positive Map, Not Technique Stack</h2>

  <p>
    The
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/">hindrances page</a>
    already gestures at the pairing: when the awakening factors are present, the
    obstructive ones weaken. That relationship is training, not a war that must be won
    before anything else can begin. Clear seeing of a hindrance loosens its grip. Clear
    strengthening of a factor gives the mind somewhere else to stand.
  </p>

  <p>
    Relative to the
    <a href="/guide/">guide</a>,
    this beat sits in Deepening — after
    <a href="/concepts/right-effort/">right effort</a>
    names prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain, and before breath and
    foundations practice spell out how those qualities mature on an object. The order is
    relative to that path. A cold arrival can still use the factors as a vocabulary for
    what is already happening in a sit or a clear hour.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course lists invite misuse. Seven named qualities can sound like seven apps to
    open in sequence, or seven achievements to tick. The texts treat them as mutually
    conditioning features of a mind in training — closer to weather that supports
    seeing than to equipment one must buy. The water that was stirred by the
    hindrances can also settle. These are names for what that settling includes.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Seven, Plainly</h2>

  <p>
    The factors named in the discourses are:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span> — mindfulness</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma-vicaya" data-en="investigation of phenomena">dhamma-vicaya</span> — investigation of phenomena</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="viriya" data-en="energy">viriya</span> — energy</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">pīti</span> — rapture</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="passaddhi" data-en="tranquility">passaddhi</span> — tranquility</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span> — unification</li>
    <li><span class="pali" data-pali="upekkhā" data-en="equanimity">upekkhā</span> — equanimity</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Sati — mindfulness</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">Sati</span>
    is the thread that does not lose track of what is already appearing —
    breath, tone, mood, thought — while it is still here. It is not a calmer
    commentary layered on the day. Without it, the other factors have nothing stable
    to lean on. With it, investigation has a field.
  </p>

  <h3>Dhamma-vicaya — investigation</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma-vicaya" data-en="investigation of phenomena">Dhamma-vicaya</span>
    is interest that looks into what is present rather than elaborating a story about
    it. Is this desire, or the knowing of desire? Pleasant tone, or the lean that
    follows it? The work is discernment, not forensic self-analysis. Investigation
    wakes energy because the mind is no longer merely drifting.
  </p>

  <h3>Viriya — energy</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="viriya" data-en="energy">Viriya</span>
    is engaged wakefulness — the opposite of the dull collapse named as
    <span class="pali" data-pali="thīna-middha" data-en="sloth and torpor">thīna-middha</span>.
    It is not grim force. Too little, and interest dies. Too much, and restlessness
    recruits the sit. Right effort’s middle tension belongs here: enough care to keep
    looking, not so much that looking becomes a contest.
  </p>

  <h3>Pīti — rapture</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">Pīti</span>
    is uplift — sometimes subtle gladness, sometimes a stronger bodily thrill — that
    can accompany deepening interest and energy. It is a sign, not a destination. Chase
    it, and craving wears practice clothes. Notice it without ownership, and it can
    settle into something quieter.
  </p>

  <h3>Passaddhi — tranquility</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="passaddhi" data-en="tranquility">Passaddhi</span>
    is the settling of body and mind — ease that is not dullness. Where rapture
    energizes, tranquility softens agitation. The two are not enemies. A mind that
    only spikes never gathers; a mind that only sinks never sees. Tranquility is what
    allows attention to rest on an object without thrashing.
  </p>

  <h3>Samādhi — unification</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">Samādhi</span>
    here is the mind gathered — not narrowed into a grim point, but unified enough that
    the object holds. Depth varies. Ordinary moments of undistracted interest already
    show a thin version of it. Absorption states explore further ranges of the same
    quality. Neither is a badge. Both are conditions for clearer seeing.
  </p>

  <h3>Upekkhā — equanimity</h3>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upekkhā" data-en="equanimity">Upekkhā</span>
    is balance that does not lean — not indifference, not emotional flatness. Pleasant
    and unpleasant still appear; the mind no longer needs to clutch or shove as hard.
    As a factor of awakening, it is the settled quality of attention that can know
    what is here without recruiting a second arrow about how it should be otherwise.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How They Condition One Another</h2>

  <p>
    The tradition often describes a sequence: from mindfulness, investigation;
    from investigation, energy; from energy, rapture; from rapture, tranquility;
    from tranquility, unification; from unification, equanimity. That order is a
    teaching map, not a railway timetable. Factors arise, fade, and return out of
    neat sequence in any given hour. Still, the conditioning picture is useful.
  </p>

  <p>
    One practical cut is the energizing wing and the calming wing. Mindfulness,
    investigation, and energy wake a mind that has gone slack. Rapture, when it is
    wholesome, can belong with that lift. Tranquility, unification, and equanimity
    cool a mind that is overstimulated. When dullness dominates, strengthen the
    waking side. When restlessness dominates, strengthen the settling side. Balance
    is the point — not optimizing a dashboard of inner metrics.
  </p>

  <p>
    However neat the map sounds on the page, lived practice is messier. A clear sit
    may show strong mindfulness and almost no rapture. A restless afternoon may show
    energy without unification. The invitation is to recognize what is present and
    what is thin — then incline skillfully — not to force the full set on demand.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Recognition Versus Manufacture</h2>

  <p>
    Most people have already met thin versions of these factors without naming them.
    A conversation where attention actually stays with the other person.
    An hour of work where interest holds without thrashing.
    A walk where the body is known as body for a stretch, and thought loosens its grip.
    Those are not enlightenment. They are evidence that the qualities are not foreign
    imports.
  </p>

  <p>
    Right effort’s cultivate and maintain apply directly. Wholesome states that have
    not yet arisen can be invited — returning to the breath, widening to the body,
    asking a quiet investigative question of what is here. States already present can
    be protected without clutching: noticing the first lean toward distraction or
    self-congratulation, and continuing. Manufacturing peak
    <span class="pali" data-pali="pīti" data-en="rapture">pīti</span>
    or deep
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>
    on a schedule is a different project, and usually a frustrated one.
  </p>

  <p>
    The difference matters. Recognition treats the factors as features of experience
    that can be known and supported. Manufacture treats them as products the self must
    deliver. One serves clear seeing. The other recruits craving under a more spiritual
    name.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Into Breath and Foundations</h2>

  <p>
    The
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">Āṇāpānasati Sutta</a>
    and the
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta</a>
    do not treat the factors as a side curriculum. Breath training, done as the
    discourses describe it, is said to fulfil the awakening factors. Contemplation of
    body, feeling-tone, mind, and phenomena is the field in which mindfulness,
    investigation, and the rest mature. The lists meet in practice: the object holds;
    the qualities strengthen; the hindrances thin.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>
      Developing the mindfulness of breathing, monks, and making much of it, fulfils
      the four foundations of mindfulness. Developing the four foundations of
      mindfulness, and making much of them, fulfils the seven factors of awakening.
    </p>
    <cite>— MN 118, Āṇāpānasati Sutta (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    <a href="/concepts/jhanas/">Jhāna</a>
    and insight use these same qualities at different depths and with different
    emphases. Stillness gathers them; clear seeing turns them toward the
    characteristics of what appears. Neither requires settling every metaphysical
    debate first. Whether deeper claims about liberation ultimately hold as ontology
    or not, living as if these factors are worth strengthening still changes how
    attention meets the hour — and that change lands in this life either way.
  </p>

  <p>
    The positive map does not replace the work of naming hindrances. It answers what
    that work is for. Obstructions can be known. Qualities that support awakening can
    be recognized, cultivated, and maintained. The path is not a hunt for seven
    trophies. It is the gradual maturing of a mind that can stay, look, settle, and
    not lean so hard.
  </p>

</article>
